<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.realpoor.com">Tarew Marr</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=daxos92>Daxos92</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/6/02 3:44:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2591.topic&index=19>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Some truth in there.</span><hr size=1> Alrighty, allow me to rephrase my points then, because everything I have said IS proven fact.<br>
<br>
Let's assume that we define &quot;soft cap on AC&quot; as the point where adding more AC has no noticable effect on your tanking. There is NO game-wide cap that has this property. It is specific to the stats of the mob you are trying to tank. If a mob has a rather insane atk rating (such as AoW or other large targets), there just isn't enough AC gear available for us to mitigate their damage down at all. This is one end of the range of difficulty.<br>
<br>
At the other end is, say, your Sol B kobolds that someone brought up earlier. By the time you hit 900-1000 AC, you are already at the point where you're mitigating their hits down as much as you possibly can. Therefore, adding more AC has no benefit whatsoever. 900 ish AC can be considered the &quot;soft cap&quot; for Sol B kobolds, but ONLY for them. Having more than 900 AC is obviously beneficial against stronger mobs.<br>
<br>
My point all along has been that 1250 is just the value that the EQ community in general sees as &quot;good enough&quot; on AC as of Luclin. Most of the uber mobs would need a completely unattainable level of AC to mitigate their hits down appreciably, and there aren't enough mobs who would benefit from that extra 100-150 ac over 1250 to make it worth striving to push that high.<br>
<br>
It's a very simple concept. The effect of your AC varies PER MOB. The way I look at this... you ALWAYS get results for adding more AC, if you measure it against a mob that is of the appropriate level and atk rating. Meaning there is no &quot;soft cap&quot; that is the same against all mobs. Then again, maybe there is, but it is so damn high that no one has ever reached it (much like the +regen and +mana caps that were discovered lately).<br>
<br>
I'm through with this discussion now, if you feel like calling these simple concepts &quot;dubious theories&quot;, have fun.<br>
<br>
Edit - how many parsing results and tests would you need before you call these &quot;facts&quot;, Brutul? People have been testing the effects of AC since back before kunark. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=443380" target="_blank">Daxos Valdorn</a><br>
55 Myrmidon<br>
